Sure! Here's an example of a recursive method in Java that calculates the factorial of a number:

public class RecursiveExample {
    public static int factorial(int n) {
        if (n == 0) {
            return 1;
        } else {
            return n * factorial(n - 1);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int number = 5;
        int result = factorial(number);
        System.out.println("Factorial of " + number + " = " + result);
    }
}

In this example, the factorial method calls itself with a smaller value until it reaches the base case (n == 0), at which point it returns 1. Then, as the recursive calls unwind, the factorial is calculated.
